<p>Here are a few common types of marketing creative that might require a creative brief:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Graphic design:</strong> Logos, brochures, business cards, brand materials.</li>
<li><strong>Ad campaigns:</strong> Concepts, copy, graphics, media.</li>
<li><strong>Website and UX design:</strong> Full site overhaul, individual pages, event product interfaces.</li>
<li><strong>Content creation:</strong> Blogs, articles, social media posts, and social series.</li>
<li><strong>Videography: </strong>Video content, animations, motion graphics, event videography.</li>
<li><strong>Photography: </strong>Headshots, brand images, product photos, event photography.</li>
<li><strong>Product packaging:</strong> Labels, boxes, containers, shipping materials.</li>
</ul>
<p>This is a good overview, but itâ€™s not an exhaustive list. If you need to align multiple people on a project, a creative brief is going to be a good ideaâ€”and hereâ€™s why.</p>
<div id="why-use-a-creative-brief"></div>
<h2>Why use a creative brief?</h2>
<p>You should use a creative brief to align all stakeholders on a marketing project or campaign. A brief that includes all essential elementsâ€”background essentials, creative direction, and follow-through plansâ€”will help avoid re-doing designs or scrapping a blog post. That means saving time and money spent on any given initiative.</p>
<p>Itâ€™s no surprise then that Monday.com found that <a href="https://monday.com/blog/marketing/creative-brief-template/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">93%</a> of marketers use a creative brief of some form to capture and communicate information for their projects.</p>
<p>Even though the overwhelming majority of marketers surveyed used creative briefs, most werenâ€™t satisfied. In fact, 67% reported that they found their briefs completely or partially ineffective.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-stat.webp" alt="why use a creative brief stat" width="500" height="598" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-77180" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-stat.webp 500w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-stat-480x574.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>If youâ€™re going to spend time drawing up a document like this for your projects, then it should be effective. Hereâ€™s how to write up a successful creative briefâ€”one that leads to better outcomes for your projects and less stress getting there.</p>
<div id="how-to-write-a-creative-brief"></div>
<h2>How to write a creative brief</h2>
<p>Hereâ€™s a step-by-step guide to writing your creative brief.</p>
<h3>1. Write a project overview</h3>
<p>The first thing you need in a creative brief is an overview of the project to identify what youâ€™re looking for, for what purpose, and how that will be completed and finalized.</p>
<p>Outlining these will avoid scope creep, which is the gradual expansion of a project&#8217;s original deliverables or requirements. If youâ€™ve ever freelanced, youâ€™re probably all too familiar. This happens when a client adds additional tasks, requests additional features, or increases expectations after the projectâ€™s already started. Often, all this ends up as uncompensated work.</p>
<p>This isnâ€™t only bad for contractors, though. When you increase the scope of the project, it often takes more time to complete and needs more communication to review and approve.</p>
<p>Having a quick, clear overview of the project will help avoid scope creep and time delays so that you can keep on track and meet your goals.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/26a1.png" alt="âš¡" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Free guide &gt;&gt;</strong> <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsite25WaysIncreaseTraffic.html?cid=Web_Any_BlogInContent_PPC_25WaysIncreaseTraffic_Download">25 Ways to Increase Traffic to Your Website</a></p>
<h3>2. Define the project objectives</h3>
<p>You need objectives for all your marketing activities, and that includes creative campaigns.</p>
<p>Take this example creative brief for PayPal below.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-examples-paypal.webp" alt="creative brief example from paypal" width="473" height="598" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-77182" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-examples-paypal.webp 473w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-examples-paypal-237x300.webp 237w" sizes="(max-width: 473px) 100vw, 473px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.slideshare.net/aaga8/paypal-creative-brief" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>The objective is stated nicely: The point of the campaign is to clear up misunderstandings about what PayPal does and make its offering super clear.</p>
<p>Now, in a perfect world, the specific misconceptions would be written out here. But this is still a good example of an objective for a campaign. What are you trying to do with the creative? Make sure this is whatâ€™s communicated to everyone involved in the project.</p>
<h3>3. Share your brandâ€™s key messaging and facts</h3>
<p>Youâ€™ll also need to include your main message or messages that youâ€™re trying to communicate with this marketing collateral.</p>
<p>Say youâ€™re working with a freelancer who is writing copy for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/09/07/google-ads-location-assets-enhancements">Google Ads</a> about your latest product offering. Whatâ€™s the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/04/27/value-proposition-examples">value proposition</a> of your product? Whatâ€™s the tagline? Whatâ€™s the positioning statement? Share your messaging essentials in your creative brief.</p>
<p>While this is especially important for any creative using copy, itâ€™s still useful guidance for visuals. It never hurts to know how best to communicate with your audienceâ€”which brings us to the next element of a successful creative brief.</p>
<p>Youâ€™ll also need to include some facts that can be used to guide your project. These could be stats, information about your brand, or insight into your audience.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/270f.png" alt="âœ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Ready to make your marketing messaging more compelling? Get the guide &gt;&gt; <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsite120WordsforMarketingWithEmotion.html?cid=Web_Any_BlogInContent_PPC_120WordsPhrases_Download">130+ of the Best Words &amp; Phrases for Marketing with Emotion</a></p>
<h3>4. Describe your target audience</h3>
<p>Understanding your brandâ€™s target audience is the key to developing compelling creative assets.</p>
<p>So include relevant details about your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/11/target-audience">target audience</a>. This will include basic demographic information, like age ranges, gender identities, or occupations. But it should also include more insight into your audienceâ€™s connection to your company. Why do they connect with your branding?</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/identifying-your-target-audience.webp" alt="questions to ask to find your target audience" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-77202" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/identifying-your-target-audience.webp 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/identifying-your-target-audience-480x308.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>If your creative partner knows the pain points that your customers experience and what motivates them to buy your solution or service, they can use this to make the designs, content, or media more personal. And <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/02/06/personalized-marketing">personalized marketing </a>is effective.</p>
<h3>5. Summarize your brand guidelines</h3>
<p>When youâ€™re working with someone outside of your organizationâ€”or even simply outside of the marketing teamâ€”you should include guidelines for your brand.</p>
<p>The other relevant brand information for this will depend on the project. For graphics, for example, this will include your colors, themes, logos, and any design rules. For content, this will include your brand voice and tone standards or your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/04/10/content-style-guide">content style guide</a>.</p>
<p>Masooma Memon, a freelance content marketer who writes the great <a href="https://masooma.substack.com/p/letter-51-5-must-use-docs-for-working" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Content Workshop </a>newsletter, recommends keeping this background short and sweet. Instead of sharing a big document, link to a quick one-pager with big dos and donâ€™ts. No one is going to be able to internalize a thick document for a single freelance project, but they are likely to go through a one-pager to make sure everythingâ€™s in order.</p>
<h3>6. Point out your competitors</h3>
<p>In your creative brief, youâ€™ll want to include key competitors. You donâ€™t need to include in-depth <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/09/21/competitive-analysis-templates">competitive analysis</a> in your project document. But you do want to include relevant competitor information.</p>
<p>For example, letâ€™s say you manage marketing for a doggy daycare and thereâ€™s only one other option in town. If youâ€™re looking for new brand visuals, you want to make sure that your colors, style, and overall creative feel are super distinguishable from your major local competitor.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-competitor-example.webp" alt="creative brief - example of logos from two businesses that look similar" width="766" height="559" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-77183" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-competitor-example.webp 766w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-competitor-example-480x350.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 766px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>If you ended up with logos this close to your competition because you didnâ€™t include it in the creative brief, youâ€™d be in trouble.Â </em></p>
<h3>7. Include any references for inspiration</h3>
<p>Letâ€™s start with a caveat: Your creative brief should include more information about your business and your products than your competitors. But if youâ€™ve got examples of amazing creative from other companies that youâ€™re looking to for inspiration, include that.</p>
<p>The best examples to use will be from businesses that arenâ€™t your competitors. You never want to copy, but</p>
<p>Take this creative from dog food company <a href="https://www.petfoodprocessing.net/articles/16103-stella-and-chewys-launches-first-ever-national-ad-campaign" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Stella &amp; Chewy</a>â€™s campaign below. This photo could be a great reference visual for photos highlighting dog leashes, pet-friendly hotels, or even hiking shoes.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-example-inspiration.webp" alt="how to write a creative brief - inspiration photo example" width="869" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-77184" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-example-inspiration.webp 869w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-example-inspiration-480x331.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 869px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3><span>8. Spell out the timeline and deliverables</span></h3>
<p>Your creative brief is different from your contract, which you should have as an agreement with any agency or freelancer youâ€™re working with. Itâ€™s your contract that will cover payment terms and timelines, as well as other aspects of the agreement such as rights, non-disclosure agreements, and more.</p>
<p>But your creative brief should include an overview of the specific deliverables youâ€™re looking for and the exact deliverables youâ€™re expecting to receive.</p>
<p>Letâ€™s say youâ€™re looking for a new logo, you need to specify what file types youâ€™ll needâ€”like .svgs, .pngs, and moreâ€”as well as any versionsâ€”like black and white, color, reversed, favicon. Those additional logos may not require additional designs, but they do require additional work. Your designer needs to be aware.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-logo-file-formats.webp" alt="logo file formats for creative brief" width="936" height="373" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-77185" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-logo-file-formats.webp 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/creative-brief-logo-file-formats-480x191.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://looka.com/blog/logo-file-formats/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>Itâ€™s also worth confirming the delivery method. Videographers, for instance, might require you to provide a hard drive for physical delivery or specify ahead of time if you need a digital file transfer. If you have a bigger project, those files will be huge. Plus, youâ€™ll need to agree on how many rounds of edits will be included and the turnaround time for these.</p>
<p>So stick a list reviewing the agreed-upon deadlines, the deliverables, and the method of delivery in your creative brief to cover your bases.</p>
<h3>9. State your distribution plan</h3>
<p>Context matters, and it should have a quick spot in your creative brief. Whether youâ€™ve got someone <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/02/09/how-to-write-a-blog-post">writing a blog post</a> or putting together graphics for a campaign, itâ€™s good for the creator to have an idea of where their project fits in your marketing.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/social-media-sites-popular.webp" alt="popular social media sites" width="678" height="750" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-76936" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/social-media-sites-popular.webp 678w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/social-media-sites-popular-480x531.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 678px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Social media assets are great examples for considering this. You can use graphics and copy across platforms, but youâ€™ll want to tailor it slightly for the different personalities of each platform. On Facebook groups and family updates are the big draw. Images are secondary on Twitter. Photos are most polished on Instagram. LinkedIn loves a long-winded post.</p>
<p>Knowing the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/01/11/most-popular-social-media-platforms">social media platform</a> youâ€™re planning to use for distribution wonâ€™t necessarily change the scope of your project. But it will make sure your designer is aware of the types of content youâ€™re competing with for user attention. Thatâ€™s helpful information.</p>
