<p><a id="tools"></a></p>
<h2>Editorial calendar tools</h2>
<p>There are several different approaches and tools you can use to create your own editorial calendar for free.</p>
<h3>Project management software</h3>
<p>Project management software like Asana and Trello are often the go-to for editorial calendars. My coworkers and I use the free version of Trello and we love it! With Trello, you have a workspace and within your workspace you can create boards. Within boards are cards where you can add descriptions, checklists, labels, due dates, attachments, and more. This makes it simple to keep track of various aspects of the content creation process.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/trello-editorial-calendar-template.png" alt="trello editorial calendar template" width="720" height="509" class="size-full wp-image-69753 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/trello-editorial-calendar-template.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/trello-editorial-calendar-template-480x339.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>You can also invite others to work on your boards. This is great for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/08/12/cross-functional-collaboration">collaboration</a>, but not the best for large teams since it can become quite messy with too many cards and labels.</p>
<p>You can upgrade to the paid version for more power-ups and powerful integration features.</p>
<p>Keep reading to download our Trello editorial calendar template.</p>
<h3>Spreadsheets</h3>
<p>Spreadsheet software like Excel and Google Sheets can be used for editorial calendars if you donâ€™t have the time to learn new software, but they are more manual and not as visual. I have made an example in a spreadsheet to demonstrate what an editorial calendar in Excel/Google docs might look like. Feel free to make your own based on this suggestion.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/editorial-calendar-template-spreadsheet.png" alt="editorial calendar template - spreadsheet" width="720" height="406" class="size-full wp-image-69755 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/editorial-calendar-template-spreadsheet.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/editorial-calendar-template-spreadsheet-480x271.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>Regular calendars</h3>
<p>Regular calendars like Outlook or Google Calendar can be good choices for visualizing and scheduling tasks fast and easyâ€”plus youâ€™ll get built-in reminders. Furthermore, you can create checklist templates with specific tasks across the different stages of the workflow, and paste them into the calendar note field to keep track of what you have done and what&#8217;s remaining.</p>
<p>Nevertheless, regular calendars might not be the best if you want to keep track of status in an orderly manner and see everything in one glance. Hereâ€™s a simple overview of how a month&#8217;s worth of planned content might look like in Google Calendar, with color codes used to identify the type of content and status.</p>
