					<description><![CDATA[<p>A simplified guide to business budgeting so you can reach your goals, grow your business, and maintain financial (and mental) peace.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/09/28/small-business-budget">How to Create a Small Business Budget in 6 Steps (+Templates)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>If you want to be successful in business, then you need to know where every dollar goes. Itâ€™s not enough to have a rough ideaâ€”it needs to be on paper. Thatâ€™s where a business budget comes in. But according to a <a href="https://clutch.co/accounting/resources/why-small-businesses-need-budgets" target="_blank" rel="noopener">study by Clutch</a>, 46% of small businesses donâ€™t have a declared budget. That&#8217;s almost half <img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f62e.png" alt="ðŸ˜®" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" />.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budgeting-basics-stat.png" alt="small business budget stat" width="720" height="412" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-64933" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budgeting-basics-stat.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budgeting-basics-stat-480x275.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Budgeting can be intimidating, but donâ€™t worryâ€”you donâ€™t need a financial or accounting background to create a small business budget. In this post, I&#8217;m going to cover all of the budgeting basics you need to know, show you how to create a small business budget, and then provide templates so you&#8217;re not starting from scratch.</p>
<h2>Table of contents</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="#why">Why you need a small business budget</a></li>
<li><a href="#how">How to create a small business budget</a></li>
<li><a href="#templates">Free small business budget templates</a></li>
</ul>
<p><a id="why"></a></p>
<h2>Why you need a small business budget</h2>
<p>In a nutshell, budgeting forces you to focus on your business objectives and serves as a compass to know if youâ€™re headed in the right direction.Â  Plus, every business goes through financial fluctuations over time. Budgeting helps you navigate these, from late payments to getting the rug pulled out from under you. Here are the key benefits of having a small business budget:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Financial health check</strong>. It lets you know if you have enough funds for generating revenue, operating expenses, and expansion.</li>
<li><strong>Achieve long-term goals.</strong> Know whether you need to cut expenses or increase revenue to achieve your strategic, operational, and financial goals.</li>
<li><strong>Grow your business</strong>. Investors or lenders will first look at your income and expenses before investing in you.</li>
<li><strong>Maintain financial security</strong>. It helps keep the doors open in case of a <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/recession-proof-small-business-ideas/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">recession</a>, off month, a downturn, slow payments, and delayed checks.</li>
<li><strong>Capitalize on opportunities</strong>. With a budget in place, you wonâ€™t miss out on any valuable opportunities for profitability.</li>
</ol>
<p>Knowing how much money is coming in and going out allows you to give every penny a â€œjob&#8221; and use every dollar to your businessâ€™s greatest benefit.</p>
<p><a id="how"></a></p>
<h2>How to create a small business budget in 6 steps</h2>
<p>Now that you understand how important a budget is, hereâ€™s how you can create one so you can ensure smooth business operation and facilitate efficient cash flow:</p>
<h3>1. Separate your business finances from your personal finances</h3>
<p>This is one of the cardinal rules to succeed in business. Itâ€™s tempting for small business owners to mix business and personal finances, but it almost always leads to disaster. Disaster in three forms:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Stagnation:</strong>Â Without an accurate view of your financial positionâ€”that is, how the business is performing with regard to its objective, youâ€™re not likely to progress.</li>
<li><strong>Taxation: </strong>It helps you manage things like business expenses for taxation purposes</li>
<li><strong>Litigation: </strong>Mixing budgets blurs the legal line between you (the business owner) and your business. It protects you from liabilities and your personal assets in case of litigation</li>
</ul>
<p>But how do you do that? Here are a couple of steps you can take when creating your budget.</p>
<ul>
<li style="text-align: left;">Incorporate your business as an S Corp, C Corp, or LLC. Then, <a href="https://venturesmarter.com/what-to-do-after-forming-an-llc/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">after LLC formation</a>, you can get your federal tax ID number and register for taxes. <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/02/23/how-to-come-up-with-a-business-name">(More tips on how to name a business here.</a>)</li>
</ul>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://fitsmallbusiness.com/llc-vs-s-corp-vs-c-corp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em></em></a><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/business-budgeting-basics-llc-scorp-ccorp.png" alt="small business budgeting basics - c corp vs s corp vs llc" width="720" height="372" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-64935" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/business-budgeting-basics-llc-scorp-ccorp.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/business-budgeting-basics-llc-scorp-ccorp-480x248.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /><br />
<a href="https://fitsmallbusiness.com/llc-vs-s-corp-vs-c-corp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image source</em></a></p>
<ul>
<li>Apply for a business checking account and credit card.</li>
<li>Use separate accounting systems for personal budgets and business finance</li>
</ul>
<p>Separating the two helps you treat your small business like an independent entity. Aside from tax advantages, you set your business up for higher profit margins. Note also that <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/14/tips-for-minority-owned-businesses">minority-owned businesses</a> can register as a minority business enterprise to receive additional support.</p>
<h3>2. Set aside a contingency fund for emergencies</h3>
<p>Murphyâ€™s law states, &#8220;Anything that can go wrong will go wrong.â€ Thatâ€™s why you should set aside a contingency fund for your business.</p>
<p>If this isnâ€™t the first <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/12/06/small-business-ideas">business you&#8217;ve started</a>, you know youâ€™ll always get surprise expenses when you least expect it. For example, letâ€™s say you operate a printing business. Then right after getting a life-changing contract, your main printer breaks down before you even start. Thatâ€™s when a contingency fund saves the day.</p>
<p>A contingency fund for emergencies will safeguard your business when these unexpected costs arise. So while itâ€™s tempting to spend that extra income to buy that new MacBook you donâ€™t need, donâ€™t do it. For now, set aside some of that money.<strong> A good rule of thumb is to set aside three to six months of your small business operating expenses. </strong></p>
<p>It will prepare you and your business in case one of your pieces of equipment breaks down, or you need to replace it. Of course, you could always take out a loan, but it wouldnâ€™t hurt to have more options.</p>
<h3>3. Identify your revenue streams</h3>
<p>Grant Cardone likes to say â€œCash flow is king.â€ Where does your money come from? How much and how often does it come in? For small business budgeting to work, you must have the answers to these questions.</p>
<p>That means tallying all your revenue (not profit) sources every month. In case you donâ€™t know the <a href="https://blog.hubspot.com/sales/revenue-vs-profit" target="_blank" rel="noopener">difference between revenue and profit</a>, revenue is all the money your business generates before expenses. After subtracting expenses, then youâ€™re left with a profit.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budgeting-basics-revenue-vs-profit.png" alt="small business budgeting basics - revenue vs profit" width="720" height="217" class="size-full wp-image-64936 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budgeting-basics-revenue-vs-profit.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budgeting-basics-revenue-vs-profit-480x145.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Sum up your revenue for the year and divide it by 12 to find your monthly income or revenue. Using this information, you can look at how your revenue changes over time. This will help you find and <a href="https://www.businessnewsdaily.com/7394-seasonal-business-stay-profitable.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">manage seasonal patterns</a> and downturns.</p>
<h3>4. Determine your fixed costs</h3>
<p>The next step in creating a small business budget is to include all your fixed costs. Fixed costs are recurring costs that are vital for your business operations. These operating costs either come up every day, week, month, or year. That includes everything from rent, debts, utilities, and payroll costs to taxes and insurance.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budgeting-basics-fixed-costs.png" alt="small business budgeting basics - fixed costs" width="720" height="450" class="size-full wp-image-64934 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budgeting-basics-fixed-costs.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budgeting-basics-fixed-costs-480x300.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://investinganswers.com/sites/www/files/_750x422_crop_center-center_none/fixed-costs-examples.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image source</em></a></p>
<p>That said, no two businesses are the same. So take some time to identify any <a href="https://bench.co/blog/accounting/fixed-costs/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">other fixed costs </a>necessary to run your business. Once youâ€™ve identified them, sum them up to get a precise figure of your fixed costs on a month-to-month basis. If your business is new, then you can project these values.</p>
<p>But ensure you factor in these monthly expenses as part of your business budget. That way, you can set aside money to cover them. Once youâ€™ve done that, the next step is subtracting them from your revenue.</p>
<h3>5. Determine your variable costs</h3>
<p>As you went through your fixed costs, you probably noticed other inconsistent expenses in your business. These inconsistent costs are known as variable costs or expenses because they change depending on how you use them. They include utilities,Â  <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/online-advertising-benchmarks">advertising costs</a>, professional development , supplies, your salary, etc.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/how-to-create-small-business-budget-fixed-vs-variable-costs.jpg" alt="how to create a small business budget - fixed vs variable costs" width="720" height="482" class="size-full wp-image-64938 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/how-to-create-small-business-budget-fixed-vs-variable-costs.jpg 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/how-to-create-small-business-budget-fixed-vs-variable-costs-480x321.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.thebalancemoney.com/a-guide-to-fixed-and-variable-costs-of-doing-business-393479" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image source</em></a></p>
<p>For example, you might increase production costs to get more raw materials to match the increasing popularity of certain products. Or if you are running a SaaS business, you might need to invest more budget in certainÂ seasons to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/09/09/b2b-sales-strategies">get more clients</a>.</p>
<h4>Discretionary expenses</h4>
<p>Discretionary expenses are also considered variable expenses because while they are nice to have, theyâ€™re not essential for your business. These include things like education, consulting, etc., which might help<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/10/07/agency-profitability-metrics"> increase profitability</a>.</p>
<p>You want to lower your variable costs in lean months, starting with discretionary expenses. And when your profits are on the uptrend, you can allocate more money to variable expenses to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/10/12/growth-marketing">help you grow faster</a>.</p>
<p>Tally all your variable expenses at the end of each month. This paints a clear picture of how they fluctuate depending on business performance so you can make accurate predictions.</p>
<h3>6. Create a profit and loss statement</h3>
<p>After gathering all the data above, itâ€™s time to assemble all the pieces of the jigsaw puzzle to make sense of it all. That means creating a profit and loss (P&amp;L) or income statement, like the one shown below.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budget-profit-loss-income-statement.png" alt="how to create a small business budget - profit loss income statement" width="720" height="465" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-64939" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budget-profit-loss-income-statement.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budget-profit-loss-income-statement-480x310.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.accountingcoach.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/profit-and-loss-statement-example-qa@2x.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image source</em></a></p>
<p>Youâ€™ve probably heard of a P&amp;L statement, and itâ€™s probably giving you a headache just thinking about it. But it doesnâ€™t have to be that way. Thatâ€™s because youâ€™ve already done the heavy lifting by collecting all the data points. All thatâ€™s left is to sum up your revenue streams and subtract the total of all your expenses for the month.</p>
<p>Hopefully, youâ€™ll get a positive figure in the endâ€”in which case, congratulations because youâ€™re making a profit. If you get a negative figure, donâ€™t worry about it. Why? You now know where your money is going and can make the necessary adjustments to turn a profit.<br />
<a id="templates"></a></p>
<h2>Small business budget templates</h2>
<p>Whether you&#8217;re looking to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/04/06/small-marketing-budget">optimize a small marketing budget</a> or get a firm grasp on all of your expenses, there&#8217;s something in this list of small business marketing budget templates for everyone.</p>
<h3>Capterra</h3>
<p><a href="https://blog.capterra.com/free-small-business-budget-template/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Capterraâ€™s small business budget template</a> is easy to use and employs all of the components we defined above, like fixed costs, variable costs, revenue, and profit. You can use it in Excel or Google Sheets.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budget-template-capterra.png" alt="small business budget templates - capterra" width="670" height="559" class="wp-image-64931 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budget-template-capterra.png 670w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/small-business-budget-template-capterra-480x400.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 670px, 100vw" /></p>
